## 3. Common Layouts and Their Trade-offs

### 3.1 Fixed Aspect Ratio Grids

<!-- TODO: Develop prose, integrate examples -->

The simplest approach: force all photos into the same aspect ratio.

```css
/* Fixed aspect ratio grid */
.gallery {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(200px, 1fr));
  gap: 0.5rem;
}

.gallery img {
  aspect-ratio: 1 / 1; /* or 4/5, 3/2, etc. */
  object-fit: cover;
}
```

**Trade-off:** Maximum space efficiency, strong visual rhythm, but **crops composition**. Photos are forced into a shape they weren't composed for.

![Square grid illustration](./assets/square-grid.svg "Fixed aspect ratio grid â€” all photos cropped to squares")

#### Approaches to aspect ratio mismatch

When photos don't match the target aspect ratio, there are two fundamental strategies:

**Cover (crop):** Fill the target area completely, cutting off parts of the image that overflow. Maximizes space efficiency and preserves rhythm, but loses image content.

**Contain (fit):** Show the entire image, accepting empty space around it. Preserves the full composition, but sacrifices space efficiency and breaks visual rhythm â€” photos of different aspect ratios appear at different sizes within their cells.

Most fixed-ratio grids use cover/crop. The question then becomes: *what* to crop?

- **Center crop** â€” the naive default. Simply takes the middle portion. Often cuts off subjects positioned using rule-of-thirds.
- **Smart crop** â€” libraries like [smartcrop.js](https://github.com/jwagner/smartcrop.js) analyze the image for edges, skin tones, and visual weight to find a better crop region. No AI required â€” just clever heuristics. The beauty is achieving good results with simple, computationally cheap operations that can run on any device.
- **AI-assisted crop** â€” services like Cloudinary use machine learning to detect subjects and faces. More accurate, but requires server-side processing or API calls.
- **Editorial tight crop** â€” an artistic choice where previews are cropped dramatically tighter than the full image (e.g., showing only a face from a full-body portrait). Creates intrigue â€” the viewer has no idea what the full image contains.

The contain/fit approach is rarely used in fixed-ratio grids because it privileges only photos that happen to match the target ratio â€” all others appear smaller, breaking the equal-presentation goal.

![Contain/fit approach in a square grid](./assets/square-grid-fit.svg "Same photos fitted (not cropped) into square cells â€” notice how the square photo dominates while others shrink")

With the contain/fit approach, the underlying rhythm also suffers. Since photos no longer fill their cells uniformly, the leading lines bend and break:

![Contain/fit grid with broken leading lines](./assets/square-grid-fit-leading-lines.svg "Fitted photos break the leading lines â€” gaps become inconsistent, rhythm deteriorates")

#### Case study: Instagram's aspect ratio shift

<!-- TODO: Develop the narrative around this -->

Instagram originally enforced square previews â€” a neutral choice that worked reasonably on both mobile and desktop, privileging neither landscape nor portrait.

In early 2025, Instagram shifted to portrait-oriented rectangular previews. For a mobile-first platform where users hold phones vertically, this makes sense.

But for existing content, this was a breaking change. Photos composed for square display were suddenly cropped differently. Subjects that were intentionally placed at the edges â€” visible in the square preview â€” were now cut off.

![Instagram â€” original square previews](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/instagram-square.avif "Instagram's original square grid")

![Instagram â€” newer rectangular previews (cropped composition)](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/instagram-rectangular.avif "Instagram's portrait-oriented previews â€” note how edge content gets cropped")

The lesson: **when you don't control the platform, you don't control how your photos appear.** Aspect ratio changes can silently break your compositions.

