### 3.2 Masonry / Column Layouts (Pinterest, Unsplash)

<!-- TODO: Develop prose -->

Fixed column widths, variable heights. Photos keep their original aspect ratio.

```css
/* CSS columns approach */
.gallery {
  columns: 3;
  column-gap: 1rem;
}

.gallery img {
  width: 100%;
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
}
```

**Trade-off:** Preserves aspect ratio, maximizes space usage, but:

- **Portrait photos dominate** â€” taller images occupy more area, drawing more attention
- **Fill order is top-to-bottom per column**, not left-to-right as readers expect
- Captions under variable-height images create uneven spacing
- Strong horizontal rhythm (aligned column edges), but no vertical rhythm (transition lines don't align) â€” monotonous vertical stripes

![Column-based layout](./assets/columns.svg "Column layout â€” portrait photos dominate visually, occupying far more area than landscapes")

The column edges create strong vertical leading lines, giving the layout horizontal rhythm. But the horizontal transitions between photos occur at different heights in each column â€” no alignment, no vertical leading lines, no vertical rhythm:

![Column layout with leading lines](./assets/columns-leading-lines.svg "Only vertical leading lines form â€” horizontal transitions are scattered, creating monotonous vertical stripes")

#### The fill order problem

CSS multi-column layout fills columns top-to-bottom, then moves to the next column. This works for text, but creates problems for photo galleries.

With pure CSS, photos fill in column order â€” the first column fills completely before the second begins:

![CSS column fill order](./assets/columns-CSS-order.svg "Pure CSS fill order: 1-2 in first column, 3-4 in second, 5-6 in third")

This becomes problematic with longer galleries. If the gallery extends beyond the viewport, the most recent photos (which users typically want to see first) end up at the bottom of the first column â€” far below the fold:

![CSS column order with long gallery](./assets/columns-CSS-order-long.svg "With 10 photos, the first row shows photos 1, 5, and 9 â€” photos 2, 3, 4 are hidden below the viewport")

Real implementations (like Unsplash) use JavaScript to control fill order, placing images left-to-right â€” the natural reading order:

![Natural fill order](./assets/columns-natural-order.svg "JavaScript-controlled order: row by row, left to right")

![Unsplash â€” column layout that privileges portrait photos](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/unsplash-columns.avif "Unsplash's column layout â€” portrait shots visually dominate")

