### 3.3 Justified Row Layouts (Flickr)

<!-- TODO: Develop prose -->

Photos arranged in rows, scaled so each row has the same width. A JavaScript library determines how many photos fit per row to keep row heights roughly equal.

Flickr's open-source [justified-layout](https://github.com/flickr/justified-layout) library takes a list of aspect ratios as input and outputs coordinates and dimensions for each photo.

![Justified row layout](./assets/justified.svg "Justified layout â€” photos in each row share the same height, but row heights vary")

**Trade-off:** Preserves aspect ratio, creates strong vertical rhythm (aligned row edges), row heights are relatively consistent. But:

- **Requires JavaScript** â€” cannot be done with pure CSS
- Horizontal rhythm varies (photos within rows have different widths, so vertical transitions don't align across rows)
- More photos per row = more regular horizontal rhythm; fewer photos = more variation

![Justified layout with leading lines](./assets/justified-leading-lines.svg "Horizontal leading lines are strong â€” but vertical transitions don't align across rows, and row heights differ")

