## 4. A Cell-Based Grid with Balanced Spans

<!-- TODO: Develop prose -->

**Goal:** Equal visual weight for all orientations in a navigational gallery.

Our approach is conceptually similar to the contain/fit strategy â€” we don't crop photos. But instead of fitting all photos to a single target aspect ratio (which would privilege only photos matching that ratio), we define **three target aspect ratios**: one for landscape, one for square, one for portrait. Each photo fits to its nearest target.

**Method:** Each photo spans a calculated number of grid cells based on orientation:

- **Landscape:** 2 rows Ã— 3 columns
- **Square:** 2 rows Ã— 2 columns  
- **Portrait:** 3 rows Ã— 2 columns

This normalizes **occupied area**, not dimensions. A portrait and landscape photo feel comparable in visual presence.

![Cell-span layout result](./assets/cell-span.svg "Cell-span layout â€” landscape and portrait photos occupy similar visual area; the result feels organic, less mechanical")

The photos appear almost randomly placed â€” no rigid grid lines visible, no strong leading lines dominating the composition. This is intentional: the layout feels more like photos pinned to a wall than a spreadsheet.

But there *is* an underlying grid. Each photo is placed within cells that match its orientation:

![Cell-span layout with grid overlay](./assets/cell-span-grid.svg "The hidden grid â€” portraits span 3Ã—2, landscapes span 2Ã—3, squares span 2Ã—2")

```css
/* Grid container */
.gallery {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(5rem, 1fr));
  gap: 1.5rem;
}

/* Spans by orientation */
.landscape { grid-row: span 2; grid-column: span 3; }
.square    { grid-row: span 2; grid-column: span 2; }
.portrait  { grid-row: span 3; grid-column: span 2; }
```

