### 4.3 The Trade-off We Accept

<!-- TODO: Brief acknowledgment -->

This layout sacrifices **space efficiency** for **equal presentation**.

When the viewport's column count doesn't evenly accommodate photo widths, gaps appear:

- **5 columns:** Portrait (2 cols) + Landscape (3 cols) = perfect fit. But portrait + portrait = 4 cols, leaving 1 empty. Landscape + landscape requires 6 cols across 2 rows, leaving 2 empty.
- **4 columns:** Landscape (3 cols) leaves 1 empty. Two portraits fit perfectly.
- **3 columns:** Portrait (2 cols) leaves 1 empty.

This happens at all viewport sizes, not just narrow ones. The wasted space is the cost of equal visual weight.

![Wasted cells in the cell-span layout](./assets/cell-span-grid-wasted.svg "Wasted cells marked with red crosses â€” some cells get trapped between spans and cannot be filled")

In this example, one cell is trapped in the middle of the layout (surrounded by four different photo spans), and five cells in the bottom-right corner remain unused. This is the price of equal visual weight without cropping.

